<a name="0">[0]</a> <a href="#0" id=0>A summary should match the reader's cognitive level.</a>
<a name="1">[1]</a> <a href="#1" id=1>A summary should match the interests of readers.</a>
<a name="2">[2]</a> <a href="#2" id=2>On the other hand, the input should match readers' interest first.</a>
<a name="3">[3]</a> <a href="#3" id=3>all core representations that match reader's interest should be included.</a>
<a name="4">[4]</a> <a href="#4" id=4>a) Core representation.</a>
<a name="5">[5]</a> <a href="#5" id=5>b) Cognitive level.</a>
<a name="6">[6]</a> <a href="#6" id=6>The core representations and the relations between them should be reserved in summary.</a>
<a name="7">[7]</a> <a href="#7" id=7>Previous evaluation methods focus on summary, which is just one dimension of summarization, and it is not reasonable to pursuit the best summary.</a>
<a name="8">[8]</a> <a href="#8" id=8>A summary should be self-complete:</a>
<a name="9">[9]</a> <a href="#9" id=9>(5) Output (Summary).</a>
<a name="10">[10]</a> <a href="#10" id=10>A summarizer can understand the input representation better if it knows more about the author, including the relevant articles and social networks.</a>
<a name="11">[11]</a> <a href="#11" id=11>a) Interest.</a>
<a name="12">[12]</a> <a href="#12" id=12>Input should also be evaluated because some representations are unnecessary for summarization.</a>
<a name="13">[13]</a> <a href="#13" id=13>Readers' comments and previous reading behaviors (e.g., the often clicked hyperlinks) reflect interests.</a>
<a name="14">[14]</a> <a href="#14" id=14>Therefore, concepts at the reader's cognitive level should be selected.</a>
